<paragraph blockId="42.[264,1325,284,1070]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Etymology: The specific epithet refers to the apparent rarity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall &amp; Cui" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rarum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Robustagramma rarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[264,1325,284,1070]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Comments: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall &amp; Cui" authorityYear="2005" box="[454,728,844,869]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rarum">
<emphasis box="[454,728,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Robustagramma rarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Cui and Marshall" authorityName="Cui and Marshall" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscuratum">
<emphasis box="[884,1222,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Robustagramma obscuratum</emphasis>
Cui and Marshall
</taxonomicName>
, new speciesin surstylar setosity and shape. Two male specimens (labelled: COLUMBIA. Leticia, pepper farm, dung, 
<date box="[766,860,924,950]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" value="1974-03">iii.1974</date>
, V. Nealis), with terminalia identical to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Marshall &amp; Cui" authorityYear="2005" box="[357,637,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Robustagramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rarum">
<emphasis box="[357,637,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Robustagramma rarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably belong to this species, but they are distinctly smaller in size (
<quantity box="[453,564,1004,1030]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" unit="mm" value="1.35">1.35 mm</quantity>
), more yellowish in color, and have smaller eyes (2.1–2.3 times genal height).
</paragraph>
